        {
            "date": "2012-02-07 15:49:48", 
            "sentences": [
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": false, 
                    "text": "@Ritesh,\n", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": false, 
                    "text": "\n", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": false, 
                    "text": "the dnsmasq for the lxc bridge explicitly binds only lxcbr0. ", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": true, 
                    "text": " So if that fails, then your other dnsmasq has already bound all interfaces.\n", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": false, 
                    "text": "\n", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": true, 
                    "text": "If /etc/init.d/lxc fails to start now, then lxcbr0 never had dhcp before. ", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": true, 
                    "text": " If you're not using lxcbr0 for your containers, then you can simply set USE_LXC_BRIDGE=\"false\" in /etc/default/lxc.\n", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": true
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": false, 
                    "text": "\n", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": true, 
                    "text": "If do want to use lxcbr0, then you should change your other dnsmasq to not bind all interfaces.\n", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": false, 
                    "text": "\n", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": true, 
                    "text": "A third alternative, I suppose, would be that you want to use lxcbr0 but your statically assign addresses to your containers. ", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": true, 
                    "text": " We could add a USE_LXC_BRIDGE_DNSMASQ variable to /etc/default/lxc to support that use case. ", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }, 
                {
                    "is_in_lex_summary": true, 
                    "text": " If that is what you want, please open a new bug against lxc and I'll add it.\n", 
                    "is_in_email_summary": false
                }
            ], 
            "name": "serge-hallyn", 
            "email": "serge-hallyn"
